sivly updated version of my Fantasy story Its rather long, and not finished yet. This is only about the first 30 pages or so of it. I'm enjoing writing it and would just like a bit of criting on it. It takes place in a world I'm making up but the time period is about 3-4ad Englandish. So here you go. Enjoy<br>
<br>
SHADE<br>
<br>
*Gostmaster*<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As Shade pulled himself across the frozen wasteland he thought back to the previous night. The last member of his group had perished in his sleep, frozen to death in this blasted cold. He was the last one left alive of that group of fifty that had come to these death lands only a month ago. They had all died from the freezing wind, sleet and snow. That kind of weather was the norm for these death lands. The others had been killed by those damn attacks by those cursed undead spear throwers. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp They could barely be seen. Most of their bodies were just bone, not a complete skeleton. Their skulls, arms, ribs and legs were the only physical parts left The rest was just not there. The arms were spaced apart and that never changed. Their joints were not attached, and they had no spine, It was magic holding them together. They hid in the snow with only their sun bleached white skulls showing. Then when some of the living would pass by they burst out of the snow with spears ready. 'Ahh yes!' He mused, 'their spears.' Made from black oak and tipped with arsenic. If you are penetrated by one you had to immediately tear it out before your blood devolved those tips letting the poison into your body. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He thought back to those fifteen men he had seen who had not been lucky enough to get them out in time. He had seen them rip off their limbs with their bare hands trying to escape from that pain. The lucky ones died early. The others they usually had to kill just to release them from that pain. Hot tears of anger and pure hatred for the undead rolled down his face as he thought of them. They had fought long and hard with him. They were the only ones left from the village. Now he was the only one. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shade lifted a hand to wipe the tears away only to find them frozen to his face. He scanned the horizon until his eyes set on a small lump of in the distance. With a small grunt he lifted his sword and trudged on, oblivious to the freezing cold arctic winds that circled him, blowing snow that almost cut out his vision. He walked on, oblivious to all this, for he had something else keeping him going. A hidden flame that was burning bright, warming him, for the only thing that kept Shade going was that burning desire for revenge. Revenge against Gostmaster. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp That treacherous creature of evil had killed Shade's entire town in his quest for world domination. He has now all but completed his goal. All except the lands east of the Krackaiden mountains was under his control. The going was tough for those left alive. The undead horde was seemingly unlimited, the living defenders were running short on men. Whenever an outpost was over run not only did the defenders lose that much land and that many people, the undead gained an equal number. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Gostmaster was not always such a creature of evil. He had once been a Knight of the Guard. A title saved for the strongest of warriors. Not all knights as the title may suggest. A large portion was, but not all. Some were berzerkers, others were archers, a small but resourceful group  were the Furfoot, ambush experts, but the smallest, most feared sect was the Darzen.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The Darzen were a strange race. They never seemed to be all there at all times. They were mentally there, but not physically. They could move like shadows, could hide in the light of the noonday sun only appearing when their attack was to be made. They seldom talked and it was even rarer for what they said to be anything more then one or two words. Their responses were usually &quot;Of course,&quot; &quot;Never,&quot; &quot;Dead,&quot; or &quot;They will die.&quot; The Darzen lived, breathed, and dreamed war, if they dreamed at all. Those were the ones who trained Gostmaster.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Gostmaster started out as a simple berzerker. When he put on his war paint and picked up his sword he was a sight to behold. At six feet eight inches he towered over most of his companions. His long black hair covered most of his face, you could only see his eyes peering out most of the time. His eyes, it could be argued were his most frightening feature. They were black as night, and the pupils had a strange reddish tint that was almost hypnotizing. Woe be to the enemy who was transfixed by that gaze. Death was all it brought. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As Gostmaster's fame grew his look grew more fearsome. After slaying the dragon Skarzblakarodereyanog, or the Brown Death as the townspeople called it, almost single-handedly, he fashioned a cloak out of the scales. A magnificent clock adorned with the teeth of the dragon and a clasp that was beautifully crafted out of one of the claws. No-one knows for sure who could make such a wonderful clasp, but people suspected that it was Darzen craftsmanship. After the Minotaur wars, where he slew the leader, Skorzbag, he fashioned  a helmet mounted with Skorzbag's horns. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp His largest accomplishment, before joining the Knights of the Guard, was the Ork assault at Stone Creek. He was with a force comprising of five hundred berzerkers, one hundred archers and twenty-five Furfoot against a what was supposed to be force of seven hundred Orks, most of them recruits. It was supposed to be an easy training mission. They could not have been more wrong. The actual force that they faced was no less then three thousand Orks. Not recruit's ether, three thousand hardened warriors lead by their warlord. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Their warlord was the rightly feared Gorefang. After some mistakes made by the general, caused by his thought that there was only seven hundred, and his grossly mistaken beliefs that one, Orks are stupid. And two, a berzerker was more then a match for three Orks, he was led into a tough spot. He, along with two hundred berzerkers, thirty archers, and five furfoots were supposed to lead the Ork hordes into the thin, deep gorge from which Stone Creek gets its name. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The remaining force was to come as soon as they heard the first explosion and attack from behind while the general lead the charge from the front. The archers would fire two rounds over their heads and the furfoot would send one karican, a mix of powders wrapped in an oil soaked cloth, lit and fired from a sling that explodes seven seconds later, before the armies would meet, unfortunately it didn't work like that. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The Ork general thought there might be a trap so he only sent about six hundred warriors after them into the gorge. The general thought this was better then expected because he didn't know about the twenty-four hundred odd warriors that had been sent to come into the other end of the gorge as a pincer movement, similar to what the general was trying to do. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The human army shot the arrows into the Ork hordes as the howling mobs closed in on them. That is when the second problem arose. One of the furfoot was a young fighter, in his first battle. When the others threw their karicans he waited a split second too long. Seeing what they were doing an Ork threw his axe catching the furfoot right in the head, almost cleaving it in half. He dropped like a stone, so did his lit karican. It exploded right on top of him setting off all of his unlit karicans, this in turn set off his companions' karicans effectively wiping out the furfoot and archer units as well as twenty-three berzerkers. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Then as they tried to regroup and attack the enemy force, now thinned down to about four hundred fifty they were hit from behind by the rest of the Ork force. They were slaughtered down to the last man. The entire force was butchered in under five minuets. They managed to take down over three hundred Orks with them. It was at about this time that the rest of the force, lead by Daniel the second in command, entered the gorge. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The front runners saw what happened and quickly ran back to the rest of the force to report their findings. Daniel decided to stay back with twenty hand-picked men to hold off the force that was moving this way to give the other's time to escape. The remaining force fled into the canyons. They got about a kilometer away before Gostmaster stepped forwards. He rallied the troops to him and laid out his ambush plan. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The furfoot, stuffed their karicans into eight burlap sacks that were then liberally dosed with lamp oil. They were placed along the narrow canyon walls in a zig-zag pattern. This went along the canyon, which was so thin it forced them to march in ranks of four, for about four hundred meters. One furfoot, the eldest, most experienced one was give the one remaining karican to set it off when the Orks were walking across it. the remaining furfoot climbed the canyon walls, aiding the archers, where they took up position hidden along the length of the trapped canyon. The remaining two hundred fifty berzerkers would stand fast, looking like  another group of rear guards. This was the group Gostmaster was to be a part of. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp His plan worked beautifully, if it can be called that. The Orks were charging down the canyon, tightly packed closing in fast. As the furfoot threw the karican you could almost make out the blood still flecked on their face. The karican landed right on one of the sack charges, setting it off instantly. The explosion tore threw the ranks sending an explosion rippling through the landscape, knocking back most of the berzerkers and a wall of fire rushing back along the canyon. Fifteen hundred of the Orks were incinerated in that explosion sending blood and body parts raining down on the archers above. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Some may have hesitated in this situation but not the Orks, they figured that what ever killed their companions was used up now and they were safe. They still out numbered the human force too. They kept charging over the bones and bodies of their companions. The archers, taken aback by this assault hesitated and thus could only fire about three arrows apiece before the two forces clashed. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The canyon widened up at this point allowing the Orks to encircle the berzerkers but due to the renewed vigor, and the disheartedness of the Orks, the battle went in the humans favor. It still might have gone in the Orks favor, but Gostmaster was in their like a scythe cutting down wheat as he made his way through the Ork forces. Of all the force only Grotfang managed to escape. After this victory, due only to the quick thinking of Gostmaster, he was approached by the king. This was when he was asked to join the Knight of the Guard.<br>
<br>
*The Darzen*<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Gostmaster was accepted into their ranks with a large amount of fanfare. With victory after victory he rose through the ranks. By the end of his second year he had reached the rank of second in command, behind only      현i- Ythert鴻, the Darzen general. He lead many great campaigns against the Ork horde, drastically thinning out their numbers. Their numbers which once ranged in the millions were now reduced to about fifteen thousand, scattered through out the lands. Battles fought under his leadership had expanded the lands under the control of the Teraidian Empire threefold.  The minotaurs, which had once been a large threat, attacking miners and trade caravans crossing the Krackaiden mountain range had been forced to leave and go to the much more dangerous Salamanderinian mountains, where the first dragons had been found. They were hard to find too. They kept to themselves, stopped feasting on livestock. Not knowing how many there were, and not wanting to start a war with the Dragons, the Empire was happy to leave them alone. The Empire, not having any wars to fight, left the army to train. This was the mistake that lead to the downfall of the Empire. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The Darzen were becoming increasingly restless. Their love of war would not allow them to be peaceful for long. They had to do something to quench their thirst for blood. They started holding late night rituals. People thought that this was strange, but they had long ago learned that questioning the Darzen never got a response. One night the period of peace seemed to be over. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Peasants started disappearing from towns in their sleep. Men, women, and children were all taken. The army was sent out but they couldn't find any evidence of what was causing it. They organized town watchmen, which seemed to cut down the kidnappings. While all this was going on in the outlying towns, in the capital strange things were happening too. 현i- Ythert鴻 and Gostmaster were often seen talking in low earnest voices along with a group of Darzen. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The people found this unusual because, the Darzen never talked with anyone. Gostmaster started attending their late night gatherings and being trained specifically by them. He was the first and only non Darzen creature ever to be trained by the Darzen. Through the training sessions he learned to control the energy around him He learned to harness it into a powerful blast that burnt though ranks of troops, leaving only charred corpses and the smell of sulfur in its wake. Until this point only the higher level Darzen could do this. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp When Gostmaster wasn't practicing ways to expand his inner power and harness it he was learning the arts of assassination. It wasn't just skill with the sword though, he was a master of that. He was learning how to hide when there was almost no cover, he was learning how to move completely silently, and he was learning the use of every weapon known to man. They also taught him in the use of poisons, potions and explosives. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp While all this was going on the kidnappings had started up again, at a rate and fury surpassing the last group of kidnappings easily. One hunting party said that in the woods they saw a light. As they grew near they heard screaming and chanting coming from a clearing. They ran over but upon reaching it they found it deserted. This kind of thing went on for a month without any change. On day, as King Tellerian was having lunch 현i- Ythert鴻 came up to him. &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;What?&quot; He asked, upset to be disturbed. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;My people wish to have the Yitaran,&quot; he said in a bleak monotone voice. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;What do you mean you want the Yitaran?&quot; He asked looking surprised, &quot;We already have the Yitaran and anyway it's just swamp  and scrub that's a hundred and fifty miles away&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;We, the Darzen, want it,&quot; said 현i- Ythert鴻 in that same emotionless voice, &quot;to live in&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Why would you want to live there,&quot; joked King Tellerian, &quot;beds to comfortable here, Oh whoops, I forgot, you don't sleep. HAHAHAHAHA,&quot; he laughed uproariously at his own joke, the visiting nobles politely laughed along with him. &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp 현i- Ythert鴻 in kept looking at him with the same emotionless, almost bored look. King Tellerian grew angry and his good mood seemed to dissolve.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Fine. Take it. Go. Now.&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp With that, The entire Darzen garrison left with Gostmaster. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The kidnappings kept up and grave robbing started up. Month after month of this went on with no contact from the Darzen or anyone who lived in the Yitaran.  <br>
Life went on in the kingdom, it was a good time. The Golden age of the Teraidian Empire. Roads were built, as were courts of law, schools and libraries. There was little to no raiding by other races and the long felt angst between the elves and the human was rapidly disappearing. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp This is not to say that it was a perfect age. There were still droughts, disease, death and all the while the kidnappings kept up as did the silence from the Yitaran. Messengers were sent but they all came back with the same story. The would walk for about a mile with no sign of anybody or any signs of civilization, then a fog would role in. It was such a thick fog that in it one could see nothing. When it lifted it seemed no matter where they walked or for how long they would always end up in the same place, the pit of the dead, fifteen miles away from the Yitaran. It went on like this for ten years at least, the Darzen were almost forgotten at that point. Then came an event to jolt their memory.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
*The Darkness Comes*<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Screaming over the lands came a tide of evil. A horde of undead warriors, the mere spectacle of them drained the fight out of most defenders and those who were slaughtered were added to the ranks. Their numbers which were originally around fifteen thousand had swollen to thirty thousand by the time they reached any opposition. The  armies of the empire joined up with a few militias from the surrounding area. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp They organized a stand at Cera Lamaralii, a fort, built on a hill. It was an old fort, many trenches, High walls of stone, and a large feasting hall made of wood and brick standing in the center. The first deep earthen trench had a wall on it as well, albeit not as tall, and made out of wood, it was still a defense. It was a good place to have a stand, and the best chance that they had of survival. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp They waited there, sharpening their weapons, and closing the gates as the last refugees made it through. They put their archers and furfoots on the ramparts that lay around the top of the stone walls From there the Archers  could rain down arrows on any enemies who passed the first wall. The Furfoot could throw karicans at any who made it to the fourth, and final trench. The northern berzerkers and the southern armored soldiers waited In the main keep. Waiting as the undead marched in. Hearing there footsteps from five miles away and feeling the ground vibrate. One young solider from the West named Kennith yelled up to the archers <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;How many can you see?&quot; <br>
One archer, a grizzled scared veteran by the name of Kin'iar glanced down and replied <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;They are more then the sand on the beach, or the needles in a pine forest. It seems as if everyone who has ever died has been brought back too fight us.&quot; <br>
Upon seeing how demoralizing this was on the troops a berzerker shouted out <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Aye there may be a million of them, but you forget, only twenty men side by side can pass through that door at a time. And we can kill twenty can't we Laddies. In fact, if I couldn't kill twenty of the bastards myself I would give up my sword and become a farmer.&quot;<br>
 &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The rest of the men began to join in the boasting and they were all laughing and shouting until a Furfoot voice rang from above them. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Eh, I don't mean ta  interrupt ya boys, But dey is just at tha gate and dey ain't stopin ta blab about how many a you dey gonna can kill, dere goin ta prove it to ya, Naw hows about ya all shapin up, an thinken of a way dat ya can keep dem from gettin ahold of ya bodies if dey slaughters us all.&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As the archers began to fire shaft after shaft into the ever moving tide of the undead heading towards the walls of Cera Lamaralii a Furfoot came up with the solution. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;If dey only gots pieces of da bodies,&quot; he said, &quot;den dere army won't be able ta do much now will dey&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp So all the spare karicans were scattered on the ground and covered with lamp oil. The fort was practically an unlit bomb at that point. One of the Furfoot suddenly let out a laugh as he placed his. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;What's so funny about this?&quot; Growled a solider working next to him. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Its jus da last time dis was used was when I served unda Gostmasta at the Battle for Stone Creek. He invented dis attack ya naw.&quot; The Furfoot replied. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;I wish he was with us now&quot; said Kennith as he put his final charge. An archer, overhearing this conversation yelled down <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Unfortunately your wish has come true&quot; as he grabbed a new quiver of arrows. The men all looked up, scarcely believing the news, <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;He's here, you mean Gostmaster is HERE!!&quot; Kennith managed to gasp out, then a puzzled look settled on his face, &quot;Why did you say unfortunately, where is he?&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;He's right out here in front, leading the charge. And you Furfoot should get up here, they're almost in range&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp All the Furfoot ran up to the top of the wall, all minus one who waited in the barracks with one karican in his hand to throw the second that the last man fell to the undead. This way, not only would they stop the undead from raising them to fight alongside them, it would also take out a large portion of the undead with them. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp A few of the soldiers and berzerkers were still in a state of shock after learning that Gostmaster. The Gostmaster of the songs and legends. The Gostmaster that they all looked up to was leading the enemy at them. They snapped out of it quite quickly though. For the Hordes had just passed the last wall. There is something about the sound of explosions, the smell of burning, rotting flesh, the screams of men as black oak spears stabbed through them and the ale being passed around to the fighters that puts thoughts of anything but the upcoming slaughter out of the minds of the men. It is has a way of gripping the mind. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The undead hordes hit the wall with such force that it caused the mortar in the walls to crack and crumble. The archers were fast using up their arrows in the seething swarm of corpses that surrounded the fort. They didn't even have to aim they just fired anywhere in their range and they were bound to hit something. The Furfoot's karicans were blowing craters in the land and drenching the walls and themselves in the blood of the fallen. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Through all the screams and explosions one noise could be heard. It was the sound of axe biting into wood. For the undead were chopping down the doors. The men in the fort began to form up. The tactic decided on was that half the berzerkers would be waiting by the doors to hack anything that came through to pieces. Behind them the soldiers would make a shield wall and behind that would be the rest of the berzerkers. The berzerkers would stand directly behind the shield wall, chopping over them while the soldiers kept there shields up and there spears pointing forwards. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As the first sword broke through the thick doors the men inside began to sing The Death song of the Defenders. The song is not a very commonly used song in battle but an appropriate one. It is about a group of men, making there last stand and trying to do as much damage as possible. For the defenders had realized that they had no chance of living, they just wanted to do as much damage as possible and at least slow the advancement of the undead. The battle did not last long after this. The door shattered and the Zombies, Ghasts, Skeletons and Wights charged in quickly overtaking the berzerkers and hitting the shield wall in less then two minutes. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The shear weight of the attackers broke the shield wall almost upon impact and the men were slaughtered the archers and Furfoot on the wall had been silenced by black oak spears since around the time that the gate fell. The defenders, were no more. One of the undead generals, a promising Wight by the name of Heru'nero-thou walked around surveying the carnage, he was about to call in the necromancers when he glanced down and saw by his foot an unlit karican. He looked at it puzzled and looked down again and saw another one. He looked around and saw it was all he could see on the ground that was not covered in the dead. He looked up and saw, standing in the doorway of the feasting hall one lone Furfoot holding a lit karican in his hand. As what was about to happen dawned on him he had just enough time to shout out &quot;RETRE..&quot; Before the explosion drowned him out. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Thirty miles away the townsfolk saw the column of flame rise and new that the defenders must have fallen. All over the country, people began to flee. The signal fire that the fort made, most likely saved a large number of lives. For the people who were not living on main roads had no idea what was going on to the East or of the constant stream of refugees heading towards the safety of the West beyond the Krackaiden mountains. The explosions were heard all over the land in a fifty mile radius and the burning could be seen at night by anyone in a two days march of the fort. People did not head to the roads, they just headed East and told anyone they came in contact with that something was coming and to get out of its path. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The undead hordes were slowed and decimated by that one attack and it did slow their advancement down, but not for long. No-one tried to stop them after that. All that was on their minds was to get to the Krackaiden mountains. There were only two passes through it and they could be better defended then just about any fort could hope to be. There was only three races that did not join the undead or flee to the Krackaiden mountains. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp These were the Orks, they disappeared to caves and the planes of the South. The Wood Elves, they refused to leave their sacred forests. The stories of trained wolf packs, giant wyrms, giant eagles, living trees, forest dragons and of course the legendary skills with a bow were enough to keep even the undead from setting one foot near their woods. The last race was the Northern Berzerkers, the ones enlisted in the army of the Teraidian Empire of course went with the army. Some who weren't left to join and some to safety, but a large percentage stayed to defend their homelands. The undead's immunity to cold allowed them to attack the lands of Norticana. Everyone who stayed behind was dead. Everyone, except Shade.<br>
