*Journey to Safety*<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp  The last territory outside the shelter of the Krackaiden to fall was Norticana, Shades homeland. He was a berzerker by nature but always disdained the Berzerker practice of wearing little to no armor to gain more speed. He wore a chain mail shirt, A large bearskin cloak and a metal cap mounted with the Tusks of a dead Minotaur Chief whose tribe had strayed to far north and had attempted to take control of Shades village. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp His village was gone now, wiped out by the hordes of undead and burnt to the ground, only five weeks ago. They had all fought to defend it, women, children, men all the surviving men from the other towns. For Shades village was the last to fall. They all knew that if they lost there, there would be nowhere to run. But it did still fall. Shade and his band of fifty had stood in the middles of the town, circling the statue of Hyrool Kanyuk, the hero who tamed the East and drove the dragons back to the Salamanderinian mountains, and according to legend, lifted the world from the plague of the werewolves. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp They made there last stand at the base of this statue and they fought back. The undead were piled waist deep around them and they still kept on coming, it was then that Shade realized that they all would die and ordered the retreat. They took a secret passage hidden in the statue and walked for three days, hearing the undead march above them, searching for them. They left the tunnels at an area known as the dead lands. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As the name suggests. It was called this because nothing did, or could  live there. It was bitterly cold and it snowed all the time. The wind, not only bit down into you. It also stirred up clouds of snow impairing your vision, though, luckily for them, it also hid there tracks so the undead couldn't follow. The undead, after coming to the conclusion that capture of them would not only be near impossible, but pointless and time consuming. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The main part of the horde headed back to the South, to get ready for their assault on the Krackaiden mountains. They left two hundred of the skeleton spear throwers, whom the legends referred to as the Hruloon, to deal with them. Gostmaster figured that the combination of them and the cold would surly kill them of. This would have been true, but Gostmaster never reckoned on Shade. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shade stopped walking and looked up as his foot touched dirt. He had made it, he had reached the end of       the death lands, He had entered the wastelands, another week of marching and he should reach the first pass through the Krackaidens. As he breasted the top of a hill he surveyed the land. There was a small corpse of trees where he could make camp about a mile to the South. Looking closely to the Southwest he was able to make out a smudge on the landscape. Shade smiled, for he had just gotten his first look at his destination. As he walked down the hill towards the trees he stopped to gather some berries growing on a bush. As he munched on them his thoughts turned to the weather, happy to be able to think of something besides just survival. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Its already November,&quot; he thought, &quot;I should hurry so I can make it to the mountains before the snow begins to fall down here. For the snowfalls are usually about thirty to forty feet in the passes. No one could pass through them, not even the undead. I would like to have a house to stay in. Empty caves are getting harder and harder to find these days.&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He entered the trees and found a suitable place to make camp, He got a fire going and took a pouch out from under his cloak. He took out of it forty-nine locks of hair held together by a warrior ring. A warrior ring is a band of Iron made from your enemy's weapon. All of Shades warriors had many of these rings. Shade knelt before the fire and through in the locks of hair one by one. As he through in each one he recited the name of the warrior whom it had belonged to and uttered the phrase <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;I have transferred your life force into these locks of hair. Because I could not burn your body I burn this and hope you make it safely to the other world. When you get there save a seat for me in the great feasting hall and save seats for your companions.&quot; <br>
After this somber rite was over with Shade fell asleep. For the first time in five weeks, feeling happy, and hopeful of the future. In the morning, he rose, gathered his pack together, had a small breakfast of roots and berries and left heading south. The sky began to cloud over as the day progressed and by mid afternoon the first drops of rain began to fall. Shade quickened his pace and drew his cloak tight around him. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He had been through enough storms to know that the one brewing was not one to be stuck out in. He kept scanning the horizon looking for a place to shelter in. As dusk grew near the storm started intensifying to the point where he could barely make out two steps in front of him. The wind howled and the rain was falling almost vertically in sheets. If the cold didn't kill him first Shade knew he would surely drown. The frozen ground could not hold much water and the flatlands he was traveling through began to flood within half an hour. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As the water reached knee deep Shade could almost make out something up ahead. It was a  hill, and on top of the hill was a house. Shade began to run through the water for the last few miles. By the time he reached the cliff the water was waist deep and frightfully cold. His entire lower half was going numb and he had trouble traversing the slippery rocky terrain of the cliff face. The water was running down the cliff almost making a waterfall for him to climb. But Climb he must for he knew he knew the lightning was drawing near and one strike near him could spell his death. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp After what seemed like hours Shade finally managed to pull himself to the top. He crawled to the door of the house and started banging with all his might. Just as he thought no one would hear him and he had climbed all that distance for nothing the door creaked open. A shaft of light hit him in the face and he looked up to see a young man looking down at him. Shade smiled and with a gurgle collapsed at the young mans feet.<br>
