*Trent*<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp When Shade awoke the next morning the first thing he realized was that he was in a bed. He was not lying on the ground with his cloak on him and his sword in his hand. He was in an actual bed, with a mattress and sheets. The next thing that hit him was he was in someone's house, and from the smell of things the were cooking up bacon and eggs for breakfast. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shade did not remember any of the events from last night and was surprised to see his armor was scrubbed and polished and hanging on the door, next to it was his cloak and lying on the chair was his sword, polished with a new edge put on it. Shade got up, took the chain mail off the hook and put it on. He left the cloak and the sword where they were and went in to meet his host. There was a young man standing there looking to be around his early twenties, late teens. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He had light brown hair with almost copper streaks running through them. He had brown eyes with the oddest flecks of yellow in them, giving them an almost pale amber look at times. He had a medium looking build but something about him made Shade think that there might be something more to him then what met the eyes. He was wearing loose fitting off-white cloth pants that ended around his mid shins and a bright red jerkin tied with a sky blue cord around his waist. He was standing in front of fireplace holding a pan on which three eggs and five slices of bacon were frying. As Shade walked in he gestured with his free hand at a table and said in a cheerful voice <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Have a seat my friend. I have already eaten, I was hoping you would be getting up soon&quot;<br>
Shade walked over to the table and sat. Within a minute or two the stranger had brought over the pan, scraped the contents onto a plate sitting in front of Shade and poured them both a glass of warmed mead. The stranger sat down and had a sip, he cleared his throat and in the same cheerful voice said to Shade, <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Hello, my name is Trent, and you would be?&quot; <br>
Shade, slightly surprised by his host generosity hesitated for a second. He then took a bit of eggs and washed them down with a swig of mead. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Hello, I'm Shade, I come from the North and&quot; Shade started, but then Trent cut him off <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Yes I know all about that, I had been told by my friends that a Berzerker, the last surviving Berzerker, from the North would be coming by. Now Eat up and we will talk more after you eat.&quot;<br>
 Trent began to get up when Shade put out a hand and said &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;I am afraid I can not stop to talk for you see...&quot; Trent cut him off again, <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Yes, we have to get across the Krackaidens before the snow falls, this I know. I meant we would talk while we walk. Now if you have nothing left to add I must finish cleaning and prepare to leave&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Trent walked out of the small kitchen leaving Shade in a bit of a daze. He wasn't sure if he liked this Trent character but he knew that two often traveled better then one. And these were good eggs. He decided to give it no more thought and began to eat again. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp After he finished he went back into his room, pulled on his cloak and strapped his sheath, stuck his sword in and walked out to find his new companion. Trent was there waiting, now instead of the white pants he was wearing brown ones of similar length and style. The Red jerkin had been replaced by a dark green one and the blue cord with a thin black leather belt. Hanging on the belt were a flask, a small pouch, a small sack and a simple brown leather sheath holding in it a strong looking sword with intricate symbols and patterns carved up and down the handle, on his back was a bow and a quiver of arrows, flight with raven feathers. Trent pulled on a simple brown, homespun cloak and together, they set off west, towards the mountains. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The going was good for the first few days. The weather was decent, a bit cold, low winds and no precipitation. Trent always found a good place to camp and the food he brought with him was serving them nicely. For if there was one thing Trent knew, it was how to cook. By the fifth day Trent and Shade could both tell that something was wrong. They were one day away from the mountains and walking through a slightly wooded area. Even at this time of the year there should be some sort of animal noise. But there was none. Not even a single eagle call. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shade and Trent, after a hasty discussion decided it would be better to just run as fast as they could towards the pass and try to make it there today, without stopping to sleep because something told them that they would not do well to wait. They quickly packed up camp, covered the fire and shouldered their belongings, just as they were about to break into a quick march they heard a crashing sound. Shade grabbed Trent and jumped to the side with him just as a black oak spear slammed into the tree they were just standing next to. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shade looked up from where the spear had come and saw a Hruloon Standing with another spear ready, behind him were five Zombies with axes in hand looking right back at him. As the Hruloon took out another spear, Shade tensed up, waiting for the time to jump, he placed his hand around the handle of his sword, ready to draw it out at a moments notice. As the Hruloons hand went back to throw the spear an arrow smashed through his skull, shattering it and the rest of the bones clattered to the ground. Shade turned to see Trent standing there with bow in hand. Shade nodded is thanks and yanked out his sword. He was about to charge right into the remaining Zombies who had started to shamble towards him when Trent reached out to hold him back. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Why do you stop me!&quot; shouted Shade, &quot;There is only five of them!&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Yes,&quot; said Trent, &quot;only five, but look out there&quot;<br>
As he pointed Shade looked and saw at least fifty shapes moving towards them through the trees. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;We can't beat all them. The best idea would be to run.&quot; As if to agree with him, five Hruloon spears clattered around them just as Trent finished talking. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;I agree, RUN!&quot; shouted Shade six more Hruloon spears flew down at them. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp They ran as fast as they could, dodging trees and roots. All the while hearing the undead following closely on there trail. As the woods began to thin out the saw there was a plain, then a hill, then they would be at the pass. After they left the shelter of the trees they put in a last final spurt, knowing that this was the most dangerous and last part of the journey. They just had to make it up the hill, they HAD to make it. They had gone to far to die here. The final burst of speed saved them. They reached the top of the hill and saw a fort with around two hundred of the Teraidian Army in it only five hundred meters ahead. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Being this close to their goal gave them the courage to take time to turn around and see what was chasing them. It was then that they wished they hadn't. They could see at least one thousand Zombies walking out of the trees, in ranks one hundred long and ten deep. After they came out there was another one after them. There was around seven hundred Hruloon, interspersed amongst the ranks and a group of around five hundred Wights and even seventy of the dreaded Ghast shock troops. More were coming out from the trees when a creature rode out on what looked to be a scaled horse. The rider had a standard, it was bright red and ragged, fluttering in the breeze with four skulls mounted on top, with long hair that also fluttered in the breeze. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shade and Trent didn't stop to see what was going to happen next, but ran right to the fort. When inside they quickly told the for commander what they had seen. All the color drained out of his face as they mentioned the mounted creature. The fort commander, an up and coming man named Tammic, had a quick conference with his sergeants. He came back to Trent and Shade and asked them, &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Are you fit to run?&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;If we have to run, we can try.&quot; replied Trent quickly.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Tammic thought about this for a second  &quot;hmmm, I suppose you can ride with me, you look as you have traveled far to be here. Wait, I will go and get the horses&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Hey, who was that mounted guy?&quot; Shade shouted out as Tammic turned to leave. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Tammic stopped, his shoulders dropped and he said without even looking back. &quot;That was Fallon. He is Gostmaster's fiercest general.  We have reason to believe he is half Darzen.&quot; With that, he walked away.<br>
