*The Bridge*<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Almost as soon as they had left the fort they heard a horn sounding from the plains below. They all started running as fast as they could away. Only stopping to pick up fallen comrades. They ran and they ran, feeling the heat on there backs as the fort was put to the torch. They could hear the sounds of their enemies' boots slamming down on the earth. They could hear their unearthly battle cries. They could smell the scent of rotting flesh following them, growing stronger. They could feel the spears whiz by them. They could hear the screams of those whom the spears had found their mark. They could see the spears find their mark too. They could taste the fear and the sweat from the army of the Empire. They could smell, feel, hear, see and taste all this, and they kept running. The adrenaline pumped through their veins and the lucky one, like Trent and Shade, held onto the horses they were riding for dear life. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp To Trent the flight to the Krackaidens was a new and exciting experience. A story to tell the grandchildren. To Shade it was just more running. Shade was growing tired of all the running. The feeling of spears slamming down where you were just standing and the sound of your enemies pursuing you was becoming common place, and this angered Shade. For he was not brought up as a runner. He was raised as a fighter. Though he knew that fighting was useless right now, and he would die instantly, it still hurt him to run. He made up his mind on this retreat, that this would be the last one. Once he reached the Krackaidens, the running would be over. He would never retreat again. As the Kavard pass, the first pass through the Krackaiden mountains, drew near Shade rode up to Tammic. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Do you think they will stop following us once we reach the pass?&quot; Shade asked. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Of course not, They were coming here. We were just in their way.&quot; Tammic replied. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Just as I thought,&quot; grimaced Shade, &quot;then how are we going to get away from them?&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;There is a bridge up ahead,&quot; explained Tammic, &quot;We have about thirty archers there to lay covering fire, and we had the Furfoot load that bridge up with explosives. As soon as we cross it, BOOM! Thing's rubble. That should hold them for a while.&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;I want to be one of the rearguards&quot; Shade quickly said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Are you serious!&quot; Asked Tammic dubiously, &quot;You do realize we won't wait for you before blowing the bridge if necessary, and you have a huge chance of dying?&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;I know all this and more,&quot; Shade aid in a tone that dissuaded further argument, &quot;I promised myself that once I reached the mountains the running will be over. If that means my death then so be it!&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;It is your choice&quot; Tammic put in sadly, &quot;But I would hate to lose you.&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;You won't then, I will take care of him,&quot; said Trent. Both Tammic and Shade jumped, nether of them had noticed Trent come over. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;You can't go! It's suicide!&quot; yelled Shade. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;I am going to stay, and there is nothing you could say or do to stop me. I have been sworn to stay at your side forever. I will not break my oath.&quot; stated Trent. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Sworn? By whom?&quot; Asked Shade. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;There is no time for that now. We have a bridge to guard&quot; responded Trent. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As they finished talking, the bridge came into sight. Shade gasped as he got his first sight of the bridge. He was expecting a bridge, maybe twenty, thirty feet long, made out of wood, or possibly stone. He was not expecting this.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The bridge was a masterpiece. It went over a huge deep gorge, at the bottom of which rushed a wide river. The Crodanan, which was also the name of the pass they were traversing, was named after the famous Vampire slayer of the past. The Crodanan was a good four kilometers wide at most parts and stretched from the Drandian sea of the North, to the Grinidian Sea of the South, running the entire length of the Krackaiden. The river, usually a fast and treacherous body of water was roaring with an unstoppable force, due to the recent heavy rainfall. It was swollen to over four times it's size and the waves were so huge that the spray would sometimes hit the ones crossing it. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The Bridge over it was even more breathtaking. It stretched the full four kilometers across and was easily fifty meters wide. The blocks  that made it up were perfectly shaped and none jutted out even the slightest. Along the sides of the bridge ran the Furfoots explosives, bundles of sticks, bottles, and sacks with small amounts of powder running out. They were placed about three meters apart and the second that the undead reached halfway across the bridge a Furfoot would blow the thing. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp No mater how many of the rear guards were still fighting. Shade and Trent, accompanied by five berzerkers and thirty archers took their places on the side of the pass to allow the rest of the men to start crossing. As the last one stepped onto the bridge The archers took their places blocking the exit. They were to hold the bridge until it was clear, then they were too run across and make it the entire way before the undead reached the halfway point across, for when they reached that the bridge was to be detonated leaving all those who  hadn't crossed stuck there. It was a risky plan and had a high chance of failure and an even higher chance of death but it was the only plan they had. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As the slow moving ox carts, full of food, treasure, and the last remaining refugees pondered their way across the first dust cloud was spotted. It was moving closer and with a cloud that big the defenders knew the approaching column of troops must be colossal. When the first undead came into sight the ox carts weren't even halfway across. That and the maddened rush of living corpses, walking nightmares, rotting putrid bodies that were only held together by magic, made Shade know in his heart that he was done for. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp After that long hard journey and all his work, his life was going to end saving some food and gold. It wasn't as they needed to keep it out of the hands of the enemy, they had no use for it. It was just because his side had it now and they didn't want to give it up. That was what Shade was going to die for. To stop a bureaucrat who had abandoned the area as soon as reports of an invasion from losing face. That was enough reason for thirty archers, three soldiers, himself and Trent to die. Knowing this made Shades blood boil. The only thing on his mind now was to kill enough to have a song written about him and to get back to the king to gather an army for revenge on the ones that killed his family. His thoughts switched quickly back to the events at hand as a spear slammed into the stone of the bridge, less then a foot away from him. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The spears began clattering down as the defenders dived for cover. All but two archers were lucky enough to get out of the way. The remaining archers quickly got up and whipped an arrow out of their quivers and started rapidly firing arrows into the approaching horde. It was slowing them, but barely. Hindering their movement slightly by the fact an arrow would thud into their chest, knocking them back a few steps. Or on the off chance they would kill one, the shambling zombies would trip over the body of their fallen comrade, causing a bit more confusion. But that's all it really was, a small confusion. A tiny annoyance. They weren't supposed to stop the undead. They were just supposed to slow them down slightly when they had to take time to cut down the defenders.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Trent realizing the small difference the group was making, started to gather the remnants of the spears and  make a small pile out of them. He then put tinder to flint and managed to make a small flame. The old, dry, dead wood caught quickly and a roaring blaze was soon created. The archers began ripping strips off their tunics and wrapping the tips of their arrows in them. The arrows were then liberally dosed in the rum some of the archers were carrying. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp While all this was going on the berzerkers and Shade, later joined by Trent had charged into the enemy sword swinging. They hacked at them until their arms were numb and weary and their eyes burned with sweat. Once the archers were ready with the fire arrows the leader, Ne'yuk-tan, Called for the Berzerkers to retreat. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The two that were fighting along Trent and Shade managed to fall back, but the three others were surrounded by undead. Back to back two of them fought, taking down as many as they could. There were two score Zombies pilled around their feet. The third Berzerker was already down, the back of his head hacked off by a Wights deadly broadsword. He was laying face down on the road about ten feet away from his two companions, buried in a pile of twenty-three Zombies and five Wights, all downed by the Berzerkers deadly skills with his six foot longsword. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shade, Trent and the two Berzerkers had made their way back to the bridge as the death howls of the surrounded Berzerkers reached them. By the time Shade looked back they had already disappeared under the tide of undead. The howl was immediately followed by the twang of twenty-eight bows and the roar of the flaming missiles flying into the approaching enemy at tremendous speeds. They flaming arrows hit, interspersing amongst the front two ranks of undead. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The undead's clothing caught, as did the dry grass they were walking on. For as luck would have it. The large storm from last night had not reached within that path, so the grass was still dry as a bone, causing the fire to race across it. Each archer managed two pull two more shots off before they two took off for the other side of the bridge. A few more Hruloons threw their spears, taking down a few more archers, before they were to busy dealing with the fire to think about anything else. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Approximately eighty percent of the Undead moved back, retreating from the deadly flame that was quickly growing into a huge brush fire. They went back away from the bridge, away from the defenders, away from the living army, away from the mountains. Back into their country,  the dead country. The country that dominated most of the known world. Where all was thought to be dead. Or would be very soon. The remaining twenty percent of this army, or around two and a half thousand  Zombies and three hundred Wights charged up the bridge. Shade and the others were running as fast as they could but were all worried that they might not make it in time.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As the Undead reached the halfway point in the bridge Shades stomach sank. He had another half a kilometer to go and the Furfoot were already lining up at the end of the bridge with karican in hand. Tammic looked up, shuddered and then gave the order to blow the bridge. But the Furfoot did nothing. They stood there, waiting, looking past Shade and his crew, looking at the undead with hatred etched into their normally cheerful faces. Pure unadulterated hatred was all the could describe it. Shade could tell they wanted nothing more then to destroy the undead who had taken away their homeland, but they remained motionless. Waiting for Shade to reach them. When he, Trent, and the rest of the defenders finally reached them one of the Furfoot. Without even looking up said. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Took ya long 'nough, tawt we was goin' ta have ta blow t'up wit ya on it if we wan'ed ta o' nah,&quot; He then jerked his head slightly to his companions, &quot;na le's blow da basta'ds back ta where dey came!&quot; <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp With this they threw their karicans at the bridge and the entire living army dove for cover. The undead saw what  was happening and ran at unimaginable speeds, trying to reach the other side before the bridge blew. But their attempt was in vain. The karicans along the side light in perfect succession tearing apart the bridge with a monstrous boom that echoed throughout the canyon. The bridge was completely destroyed, sending chunks of rock all over the mountain in a one kilometer radius, setting of a few avalanches into the river. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp It was a stupendous display of fire power and when Shade got up to look around he saw no sign of the undead, and the only sign of the bridge, besides the rock covering the landscape, was two chard towers, where the sides of the bridge used to start. The road leading from the bridge was blackened as well. Rocks were still raining down on them and they knew finally that they were safe. <br>
