*The Trip to Herigen*<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The rest of the trip back to Harigen, the capital of the Teraidian Empire, was uneventful. At full march it took then four days to reach it. They took the Royal Road and all along it they could see the villagers burying their precious goods, fortifying their houses, making sure all the food was safely packed away, making sure the signal fire was ready, and making sure that an escape would be easy and fast. In short, they were preparing for war. If the news of the fall of everywhere outside the mountains hadn't reached them, the constant stream of refugees would have tipped them off that something was wrong. People kept running up to the troops and trying to get some information out of them. But Tammic had already forbid them to tell anything, save that they should prepare. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The Royal Road was long, mainly flat, mainly straight. It was constructed hundreds of years ago, under the guidance of King Har'nktola the Second. It went from both passes through the Krackaidens to the Capital, Harigen. Other roads connected onto it, and branched off of it along the way, but none were near the size, and quality of the Royal Road. On the other side of the Krackaidens, the road leading to the Crodanan pass started out in the old capital of Gerendenan. Lower down, at the Hatnitshut pass the road started out in the Elven/Human trading city of Herun'knuck. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp On the last day of their journey Shade awoke early at the small camp they had set up last night. They were beside a forest on one side, and a stream on the other. They had a fire, still smoldering slightly in the center, all around it were the men, sleeping on the ground, some with a blanket or cloak thrown over them, the others just in their normal clothes. Shade stood up, brushing the dew off himself and stretched as the first rays of sun started to peak through the trees. The first thing he noticed was that Trent, was missing. He decided to go look for him, since he was already awake and felt like the walk would clear his mind. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp After about twenty minutes of walking he started hearing a low chanting coming from the forest. He cautiously entered the trees, not knowing what to expect and going silently so as not to scare whatever it was away. As he grew nearer to the sound he began to be able to make out a light, glowing amongst the trees. Figuring that was probably where the sound was coming from he got down and crawled over, making sure not to be seen. When he got close to the light he saw a rather queer sight. It was Trent, sitting on a stump in the middle of a small clearing. Well he wasn't exactly sitting, he was in fact levitating a few centimeters off the stump. The light was caused by a strange phosphoric fog that was swirling around him as he meditated. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Shade quickly left, not wanting Trent to discover him. Shade returned to the camp to find everyone up and awake, just in time to start breakfast. By the time they had all eaten Trent had made his way back and was shouldering his pack. Shade gave him a quick look but did not say anything to him. The march started up again but Shade could not stop thinking about what he saw. By mid-afternoon Shade was no closer to finding an answer then when he started. The company had opted to skip lunch and keep marching. For, as Tammic pointed out, they were close to Harigen, and there they were promised a feast. As they breasted the final hill all thoughts of what he had seen that morning left Shade. For, looking at the beauty of Harigen, the only sound anyone in the company could muster was a gasp. <br>
